"Abstract As EDI becomes established, its success will mean that business and government organisations will become ever more operationally dependent on Information and Communications Technology (IACT) than hitherto. The ensuing proliferation of EDI networks creates problems for the certification of output from such systems for presentation as admissible evidence in a UK court of law. Trade transactions contracted over such computer and communications networks have the disadvantage of being ‘fleeting’ and therefore it could be difficult to produce an authenticated record of what has occurred between parties in the event of a dispute. In addition, as new legislation (such as the Computer Misuse Act 1990 ) demands higher standards of security from corporate network managers, the procedures, techniques and technologies of system access control, user authorisation and transaction verification will increasingly be under forensic scrutiny. This article drawn on research studies (the VERDICT and APPEAL Reports) carried out by CASTELL for the Central Computer and Telecommunications Agency (CCTA, HM Treasury) during 1987 and 1988 reviewing the UK position on legal admissibility, and assessing the ‘legal reliability’, of computer generated evidence. Preliminary guidelines drafted as the outcome of further work carried out for the CCTA's GOSIP EDI Task Force (the ‘EDILAW ONE’ Report) are presented."
